Robert Iger, Head of Disney, May Not Be Leaving Anytime Soon



Breakingviews 
By                     
JENNIFER SABA

FEB. 6, 2017




Continue reading the main story
Share This Page

Continue reading the main story









Robert A. Iger may swing for a three-peat. The Walt Disney chief executive is considering delaying for the third time his departure from atop the House of Mouse. It’s a sign that the entertainment conglomerate has failed to find a replacement for him since Tom Staggs left last year. Clinging to power, though, can get messy.Executives at Disney are betting that Mr. Iger, who has run the company for 12 years and will turn 66 on Friday, will have to stick around longer, according to a report in The Wall Street Journal. By all accounts, Mr. Iger is a worthy boss. After he took over in 2005, Disney’s market value rose from $46 billion to about $148 billion at the end of its 2016 fiscal year. Total shareholder return over the same period increased 350 percent, Disney said in its proxy.Beyond the numbers, Mr. Iger has improved the company by making savvy acquisitions such as the $4 billion deal for the “Star Wars” studio, Lucasfilm. And no company is better at cross-promoting its products: Princess Elsa costumes from the animated movie “Frozen” are a big hit with toddlers, for example.

Advertisement

Continue reading the main story

A successor will need time and guidance to learn the ways of Disney’s sprawling divisions, from movie studios to theme parks to cable networks. Challenges are cropping up, too: The cable sports network ESPN, traditionally the company’s biggest money-spinner, is losing subscribers as more people drop paid-TV packages. Navigating the hurdles of changing news media habits will take exceptional fortitude. Continue reading the main story







Advertisement

Continue reading the main story





A chief executive’s longevity can bring needed experience and stability. That’s useful in a crisis: Lloyd Blankfein at Goldman Sachs and JPMorgan Chase’s Jamie Dimon have run their companies for almost as long as Mr. Iger has. But it can also store up resentment among underlings and risk complacency. Richard S. Fuld Jr., for example, headed Lehman for 14 years before its collapse.Mr. Iger has a cautionary tale much closer to home: His predecessor Michael Eisner’s 21 years in command ended after a series of bumbling decisions and his rancorous spat with Michael Ovitz, Disney’s former president, led to an investor revolt.Mr. Iger has been good for Disney, but he, too, risks overstaying his welcome. Continue reading the main story






